data.content:
Yes — the direct cast will throw `InvalidCastException` on failure, giving a confusing test error. Use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` instead:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

This gives a clear failure message like *"Expected type EmailHandler, got SmsHandler"*. The generic overload (`IsInstanceOfType<T>`) is available in MSTest v3+; for older versions use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler))`.

If you also need the typed reference, you can combine it with a pattern:

```csharp
Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
if (result is EmailHandler handler)
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
```
